    "the_wonder": "In the Milne Bay Province of Papua New Guinea, across a ring of eighteen islands, local tribes practice a system of exchange that puzzled early Western economists: the Kula Ring. Men build large, ocean-going canoes and sail hundreds of miles across open ocean to visit other islands, facing dangerous currents to trade shell necklaces and armbands.\n\nWhat is astonishing is that the traded objects have no physical utility and are never kept for long. Red shell necklaces travel clockwise around the ring, while white shell armbands travel counter-clockwise. A man holds an object for only a few months before passing it to the next partner. The shells are never bought or sold, and their value is determined entirely by their history and the prestige of the men who have held them.\n\nLinguist Bronisław Malinowski studied the Kula Ring in the 1910s and discovered that the exchange is the foundation of local political and social life. It builds trust, establishes long-distance alliances, and prevents war across separated island communities. The Kula Ring proves that economic systems can be built around the exchange of relationships and prestige rather than material utility, showing a unique model of wealth.",
