    "the_wonder": "For centuries, humanity wondered if our solar system was unique, and if there were other worlds capable of supporting liquid water and life. Early exoplanet discoveries yielded only hot Jupiters—gas giants orbiting dangerously close to their stars. The launch of NASA's Kepler space telescope in 2009 changed everything, allowing astronomers to search for tiny dips in starlight caused by orbiting planets.\n\nIn April 2014, scientists announced the discovery of Kepler-186f, the first validated Earth-sized planet orbiting in the habitable zone of another star. Located 580 light-years away in the constellation Cygnus, Kepler-186f orbits an M-dwarf star, which is cooler and smaller than our Sun. The planet is about 10% larger than Earth in diameter and receives about one-third of the solar energy that Earth does, putting it on the outer edge of its star's habitable zone.\n\nBecause of its size and location, Kepler-186f is likely a rocky world with a surface temperature that could allow liquid water to pool under a suitable atmosphere. While we cannot yet verify its atmospheric composition or the presence of water, the discovery proves that Earth-sized planets in habitable zones are common in the galaxy, bringing us closer to answering if we are alone in the universe.",
