    "the_wonder": "In northwestern Venezuela, where the Catatumbo River empties into Lake Maracaibo, the sky is almost permanently on fire. For up to 300 nights a year, this small region experiences a continuous, intense storm that produces silent, bright flashes of lightning. The lightning strikes are so frequent and regular that the phenomenon has been used by sailors as a natural lighthouse for centuries.\n\nThe storm begins shortly after dusk, producing up to 280 lightning strikes per hour, lasting for up to ten hours a night. The phenomenon is created by a unique combination of topography and wind currents. Cold winds blowing from the Andes mountains collide with the warm, humid air rising from the swampy waters of Lake Maracaibo, creating a permanent, highly unstable updraft that triggers electrical discharges.\n\nUnlike typical thunderstorms, the Catatumbo lightning is often silent because the discharges occur high in the cloud layers, far from the ground. It is considered the world's largest single generator of tropospheric ozone, playing a vital role in regenerating the Earth's ozone layer. Despite changes in climate patterns, the storm continues to flash, serving as a striking monument to atmospheric energy.",
