    "the_wonder": "Hovering over isolated mountain peaks like Mount Rainier or Mount Fuji, saucer-shaped clouds sometimes form in the sky. These 'lenticular clouds' (Altocumulus lenticularis) are perfectly smooth, lens-shaped clouds that remain stationary in the air, even when strong winds blow. Because of their clean, geometric shapes, they are frequently mistaken for UFOs by casual observers.\n\nLenticular clouds are created by a process of atmospheric wave motion. When strong, humid winds blow over a mountain peak, they create a wave of air on the downwind side. As the air rises to the crest of the wave, it cools, and the moisture condenses into cloud droplets. As the air descends down the other side of the wave, it warms, and the droplets evaporate.\n\nThis continuous cycle of condensation at the front and evaporation at the back makes the cloud appear stationary, even though air is constantly flowing through it at high speeds. The cloud acts as a physical marker of an invisible wave in the atmosphere, showing the dynamic, flowing nature of our air currents over mountains.",
