    "wonder_title_hi": "फर्मी विरोधाभास",
    "the_wonder": "In 1950, physicist Enrico Fermi was walking to lunch with colleagues at the Los Alamos National Laboratory when the conversation turned to flying saucers and extraterrestrial life. Fermi famously asked his companions, 'Where is everybody?' This simple question became the foundation of the Fermi Paradox: the contradiction between the high probability of extraterrestrial civilizations and the complete lack of evidence for them.\n\nThe logic is simple: there are billions of stars in our galaxy that are older than our Sun. Many of these stars host Earth-like planets. If life is common, some of these civilizations should have developed space travel and colonized the galaxy over millions of years. Even at slow speeds, the entire galaxy could be traversed in a fraction of its geological age. Yet, search projects like SETI have detected nothing but silent, empty space.\n\nHypotheses to resolve the paradox range from the mundane to the terrifying. The 'Great Filter' theory suggests that there is a developmental barrier that almost all life fails to pass—such as self-destruction via technology. The 'Zoo Hypothesis' suggests aliens are observing us without intervening, while the 'Dark Forest' theory proposes that civilizations remain silent to avoid being destroyed by apex predators. The paradox remains unsolved, leaving us to wonder if we are truly alone.",
    "why_it_matters": "The Fermi Paradox forces us to confront the rarity and fragility of conscious life. It suggests that our survival is not guaranteed, and that the silence of the cosmos may be a warning about the self-limiting nature of technological progress.",
