    "the_wonder": "For centuries, the Great Wall of China dominated the history of massive defensive structures. However, in northeastern Iran, archaeologists have uncovered the remains of a defensive system that was built with comparable speed and engineering sophistication: the Great Wall of Gorgan. Stretching 195 kilometers from the Caspian Sea to the mountains, it is the longest defensive wall in Western Asia.\n\nBuilt by the Sasanian Persian Empire in the 5th century CE, the wall was constructed using tens of millions of red bricks, which were fired in thousands of kilns built along the route. The wall featured 38 forts, housing a garrison of 30,000 soldiers, and a complex canal system that acted as both a water supply and a defensive moat. It was built to protect the fertile Gorgan plain from the raids of northern nomadic tribes.\n\nDespite its massive size and sophisticated design, the wall was completely abandoned after the Arab conquest of Persia and gradually swallowed by the desert sands. Today, it is barely visible from the ground, looking like a low ridge in the landscape. The Wall of Gorgan shows that even the most massive, red-brick monuments of empire can vanish into the earth, leaving only faint outlines for archaeologists to discover.",
